1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,707
[Soft piano music fades in

2
00:00:02,707 --> 00:00:05,415
A dark void

3
00:00:05,415 --> 00:00:08,123
] “Picture, for a moment, every possible straight-line motion in the plane

4
00:00:08,123 --> 00:00:10,830
Each one has a direction, a length, and—crucially—a place it starts

5
00:00:10,830 --> 00:00:13,538
But if we agree to draw every one of them starting from the same dot

6
00:00:13,538 --> 00:00:16,246
suddenly the world becomes… simpler

7
00:00:16,246 --> 00:00:18,953
” [Fade-in of a faint Cartesian grid

8
00:00:18,953 --> 00:00:21,661
A single red arrow grows from the origin, tip glowing

9
00:00:21,661 --> 00:00:24,369
] “This arrow is called a vector

10
00:00:24,369 --> 00:00:27,076
It’s not just a point

11
00:00:27,076 --> 00:00:29,784
it’s the idea of moving 3 units right

12
00:00:29,784 --> 00:00:32,492
no matter where you start

13
00:00:32,492 --> 00:00:35,199
We package that idea into a neat column of numbers—here

14
00:00:35,199 --> 00:00:37,907
the vector **v** = [3

15
00:00:37,907 --> 00:00:40,615
” [The coordinates appear beside the arrow, then gently slide underneath it

16
00:00:40,615 --> 00:00:43,323
] “Now, what happens if we allow ourselves two of these arrows

17
00:00:43,323 --> 00:00:46,030
Or… all of them

18
00:00:46,030 --> 00:00:48,738
” [Duplicate arrows in muted colors fade in across the plane

19
00:00:48,738 --> 00:00:51,446
all rooted at the origin

20
00:00:51,446 --> 00:00:54,153
The camera slowly zooms out, revealing an endless constellation of arrows

21
00:00:54,153 --> 00:00:56,861
] “Together they form a space—not empty

22
00:00:56,861 --> 00:00:59,569
bursting with every possible direction

23
00:00:59,569 --> 00:01:02,276
We call this collection a vector space

24
00:01:02,276 --> 00:01:04,984
It’s the set of all vectors you can reach by stretching

25
00:01:04,984 --> 00:01:07,692
flipping a few building-block arrows

26
00:01:07,692 --> 00:01:10,399
” [The swarm of arrows dims, leaving only three: red, green, blue

27
00:01:10,399 --> 00:01:13,107
They stretch

28
00:01:13,107 --> 00:01:15,815
reverse in real time

29
00:01:15,815 --> 00:01:18,523
their tips tracing out the entire plane

30
00:01:18,523 --> 00:01:21,230
] “And here’s the quiet miracle: Every point you see is reachable by some combination of these arrows

31
00:01:21,230 --> 00:01:23,938
The plane itself has become an algebraic object

32
00:01:23,938 --> 00:01:26,646
governed by two simple rules—add vectors

33
00:01:26,646 --> 00:01:29,353
” [The grid lines brighten

34
00:01:29,353 --> 00:01:32,061
the word “Vector Space” materializes overhead in white

35
00:01:32,061 --> 00:01:34,769
] “In the next episode we’ll ask the obvious next question: If every vector is a path

36
00:01:34,769 --> 00:01:37,476
which paths are truly necessary

37
00:01:37,476 --> 00:01:40,184
How few arrows can paint the entire picture

38
00:01:40,184 --> 00:01:42,892
” [Music resolves

39
00:01:42,892 --> 00:01:45,599
Fade to black
